{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491572"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"987"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/987"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.15,0.09,0.63,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55105"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/987"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40623"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55105"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of coughing up small quantities of fresh blood. She reports feeling feverish and experiencing night sweats. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Six weeks ago, she returned from Zimbabwe where she had been working for an NGO for six months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is raised but not pulsatile. Supraclavicular lymphadenopathy is present. On auscultation, rhonchi are heard over the upper lobes of both lungs. Percussion reveals dullness over the left upper lobe. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT scan of the chest","Interferon-gamma release assay","Tuberculin skin test","Sputum microscopy with acid-fast stain","Sputum culture and susceptibility testing"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presentation is highly suggestive of pulmonary tuberculosis. The patient presents with classic symptoms including haemoptysis, fever, and night sweats, along with a recent history of travel to a high-prevalence area (Zimbabwe). The examination findings are consistent with mild segmental collapse of the upper lobes bilaterally and possible cavitation of the left upper lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next investigation in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Esputum microscopy with acid-fast stain\u003C/strong\u003E. This, along with a chest x-ray, are the first-line investigations for suspected tuberculosis in a symptomatic patient. Sputum microscopy with acid-fast stain is rapid and inexpensive, making it an excellent initial test. A positive result suggests the patient is at risk of transmitting tuberculosis, but will not provide information on drug susceptibility. In practice a Nucleic Acid Amplification Test (NAAT) and sputum tuberculosis cultures would be performed simultaneously. NAAT has a higher sensitivity than sputum microscopy with acid-fast staining, but is less sensitive than cultures. Both of these methods will provide insight into drug susceptibility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum culture and susceptibility testing\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed necessary to confirm the diagnosis and assess for drug resistance. However, it is not the most appropriate next step as it can take several weeks to yield results. It should be performed in conjunction with microscopy, but is not the immediate priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the chest\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in identifying active tuberculosis following an inconclusive chest x-ray, but it is not the standard first-line investigation. It may be considered later if initial tests are inconclusive but clinical suspicion remains high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculin skin test\u003C/strong\u003E (or Mantoux test) and \u003Cstrong\u003Einterferon-gamma release assay\u003C/strong\u003E (such as QuantiFERON-TB Gold) are primarily used to detect latent tuberculosis infection. They have limited utility in diagnosing active pulmonary tuberculosis in a symptomatic patient, especially one from a high-prevalence area where these tests may be positive due to prior exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, given the high clinical suspicion for active pulmonary tuberculosis, the priority is to obtain sputum samples for microscopy and culture, along with a chest X-ray. This approach allows for rapid initial assessment (microscopy) while also setting up for definitive diagnosis (culture).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chest x-ray and sputum microscopy with an acid-fast stain are the first-line investigations in a symptomatic patient with suspected pulmonary tuberculosis.","Classic symptoms of pulmonary tuberculosis include cough, haemoptysis, fever, and night sweats."],"references":["Tuberculosis. In: Therapeutic guidelines [online]. Updated 2022 Aug; accessed 2022 Oct 6. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etg","Coulter C. Tuberculosis testing. Aust J Gen Pract. 2012 Jul 10;41:489\u201392. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/july/tuberculosis-testing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40623"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"987"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17728"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17728"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/13db6fb9-3022-43bd-b0a3-c2027fa24cfb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/13db6fb9-3022-43bd-b0a3-c2027fa24cfb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":514,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40623"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T17:57:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T17:57:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"987"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55105"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0